{"Body": "<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Oireachtas Public Accounts Committee will discuss on November 26 if Trinity&rsquo;s Student Service Charge is being used to top up the College&rsquo;s core grant. The Committee will discuss that matter in a closed session.</p>\n<p>The Joint Education and Science committee heard that only a third of Trinity&rsquo;s student service charge for 2008/09 academic year was spent on student services. The accounts produced by Trinity College were sent to the chairman of the education committee and Green party TD Paul Gogarty.</p>\n<p>Gogarty told the committee that the accounts sent to him by Trinity SU&rsquo;s president C&oacute;n&aacute;n &Oacute; Broin revel that much of the student service charge is being used to pay for cuts in the Government&rsquo;s grant to the College.</p>\n<p>The student service charge is supposed to be ring fenced for student services, exams, and registration. The charge has increased this year to &euro;1,500 from &euro;900 the year before.</p>\n<p>&Oacute; Broin says that the documents that he has sent to the Oireachtas education committee show that of the &euro;1,500 student service charge &lsquo;less than thirty-five per cent is actually being spent of student services.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>Fine Gael education spokesman Brian Hayes, TD has said that he has written to the Comptroller and Auditor General and asked for an immediate investigation into the student service charge &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Hayes told the education committee that the student service charge is &lsquo;tuition fees through the back door.&rsquo;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The estimate accounts for 2009 show that of the &euro;900 charge only &euro;593.75 was being spent on student services the rest was being used to make up for cuts in the core grant given to the College by the Higher Education Authority (HEA).</p>\n<p>The HEA wrote to the College in 2002 and said that there would be a &euro;250 reduction in the College&rsquo;s grant. Then again in 2008 the HEA told the College that there would be a further reduction which, when calculated on 2009 figures, amounts to &euro;56.25.</p>\n<p>The College is making up for this reduction by taking these amounts from the student service charge. This was &lsquo;direct evidenc\n<script src=\"tiny_mce/themes/advanced/langs/en.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\ne that students are being fleeced and the charge is not related to student services,&rsquo; Hayes said.</p>\n<p>In a letter to Gogarty explaining Trinity SU&rsquo;s argument on the student service charge &Oacute; Broin says that the Minister for Education is on record saying that the student service charge is &lsquo;solely for the provision of student services.&rsquo;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&lsquo;The Minister is either wilfully ignorant of this situation, or else has been deliberately misleading the public,&rsquo; says &Oacute; Broin.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The College says that the &lsquo;student charge supports on average up to eighty to eighty-five per cent of the full costs of providing student services. The balance of the funding for the student services in Trinity College is met from income generated by the College.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>UCD&rsquo;s students&rsquo; union released a statement saying that only &euro;505 of their &euro;1,500 student service charge is spent on student services.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>UCD students&rsquo; union&rsquo;s president Gary Redmond said that &lsquo;students are paying more in their registration fee each year, but seeing less of a return.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>The HEA said that they would be happy to receive details of the claims made by Trinity Students&rsquo; Union and UCD students&rsquo; union. They then went on to say that in many cases, the student service charge did not meet the non-academic costs of education.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&Oacute; Broin has received a letter from the Joint Committee of Education and Science to the Minister for Education asking him to respond to the issues raised in the documents.</p>\n<p>The student service charge was introduced in 1996 when the Government started to pay tuition fees. A charge of &pound;150 was paid by students for services, registration, and examinations.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Department for Education circular on the student service charge says that examination and registration fees have always been regarded as a separate issue. &lsquo;Second level students pay an examination fee for sitting the Junior and Leaving Certificate examination,&rsquo; the circular says.</p>\n<p>The estimates for 2009 say that the College collected &euro;8,283,371 from student service charge. The estimates also indicate that the College budgeted &euro;1,351,000 for examinations and &euro;1,435,425 on the costs of registration for 2009.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "Imageurl": "<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Oireachtas Public Accounts Committee will discuss on November 26 if Trinity&rsquo;s Student Service Charge is being used to top up the College&rsquo;s core grant. The Committee will discuss that matter in a closed session.</p>\n<p>The Joint Education and Science committee heard that only a third of Trinity&rsquo;s student service charge for 2008/09 academic year was spent on student services. The accounts produced by Trinity College were sent to the chairman of the education committee and Green party TD Paul Gogarty.</p>\n<p>Gogarty told the committee that the accounts sent to him by Trinity SU&rsquo;s president C&oacute;n&aacute;n &Oacute; Broin revel that much of the student service charge is being used to pay for cuts in the Government&rsquo;s grant to the College.</p>\n<p>The student service charge is supposed to be ring fenced for student services, exams, and registration. The charge has increased this year to &euro;1,500 from &euro;900 the year before.</p>\n<p>&Oacute; Broin says that the documents that he has sent to the Oireachtas education committee show that of the &euro;1,500 student service charge &lsquo;less than thirty-five per cent is actually being spent of student services.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>Fine Gael education spokesman Brian Hayes, TD has said that he has written to the Comptroller and Auditor General and asked for an immediate investigation into the student service charge &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Hayes told the education committee that the student service charge is &lsquo;tuition fees through the back door.&rsquo;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The estimate accounts for 2009 show that of the &euro;900 charge only &euro;593.75 was being spent on student services the rest was being used to make up for cuts in the core grant given to the College by the Higher Education Authority (HEA).</p>\n<p>The HEA wrote to the College in 2002 and said that there would be a &euro;250 reduction in the College&rsquo;s grant. Then again in 2008 the HEA told the College that there would be a further reduction which, when calculated on 2009 figures, amounts to &euro;56.25.</p>\n<p>The College is making up for this reduction by taking these amounts from the student service charge. This was &lsquo;direct evidenc\n<script src=\"tiny_mce/themes/advanced/langs/en.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"></script>\ne that students are being fleeced and the charge is not related to student services,&rsquo; Hayes said.</p>\n<p>In a letter to Gogarty explaining Trinity SU&rsquo;s argument on the student service charge &Oacute; Broin says that the Minister for Education is on record saying that the student service charge is &lsquo;solely for the provision of student services.&rsquo;&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&lsquo;The Minister is either wilfully ignorant of this situation, or else has been deliberately misleading the public,&rsquo; says &Oacute; Broin.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The College says that the &lsquo;student charge supports on average up to eighty to eighty-five per cent of the full costs of providing student services. The balance of the funding for the student services in Trinity College is met from income generated by the College.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>UCD&rsquo;s students&rsquo; union released a statement saying that only &euro;505 of their &euro;1,500 student service charge is spent on student services.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>UCD students&rsquo; union&rsquo;s president Gary Redmond said that &lsquo;students are paying more in their registration fee each year, but seeing less of a return.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>The HEA said that they would be happy to receive details of the claims made by Trinity Students&rsquo; Union and UCD students&rsquo; union. They then went on to say that in many cases, the student service charge did not meet the non-academic costs of education.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&Oacute; Broin has received a letter from the Joint Committee of Education and Science to the Minister for Education asking him to respond to the issues raised in the documents.</p>\n<p>The student service charge was introduced in 1996 when the Government started to pay tuition fees. A charge of &pound;150 was paid by students for services, registration, and examinations.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Department for Education circular on the student service charge says that examination and registration fees have always been regarded as a separate issue. &lsquo;Second level students pay an examination fee for sitting the Junior and Leaving Certificate examination,&rsquo; the circular says.</p>\n<p>The estimates for 2009 say that the College collected &euro;8,283,371 from student service charge. The estimates also indicate that the College budgeted &euro;1,351,000 for examinations and &euro;1,435,425 on the costs of registration for 2009.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "460", "Heading": "Oireachtas to investigate spending of registration fee"}